			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Horizone&amp;amp;lt;&amp;amp;lt;&amp;amp;lt;&amp;amp;lt;curious about<a name="27129"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Mar 12 04 2:56 AM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>I played the free trial (I think it's still going, it's at some weird website though; do a search for it and you might find it).
<br />

<br />
Frankly, if you've played AC2, it's very, very similar in terms of interface, appearance and storyline.  The skills work the same way, with the greyed-out uses.  The worlds seem as deserted (I played for 7 days and never spoke to 1 person, literally, never heard one person speak).
<br />

<br />
In the differences category, there are a LOT of different classes, about 8 basic and a lot more advanced that stem from having those basic ones or skills obtained from them at different levels.  The same goes for crafting.
<br />

<br />
There is a lot of multiclassing, in that you're allowed to be in as many schools as you want, but with only one active adventure and crafting school at a time (you can change your active one by going to a trainer at your whim).  When you're in a different class, there are limitations placed on which abilities you can use from your other classes, mostly restricted to those at 1/2 of your current class's level.  The bad side of multiclassing is that it gives you a higher adventure level, which means that you'll get less EXP for fighting creatures.  AFAIK there's no cap on how many schools you can join or how high an overall level you can get, but there's a Level 100 cap in each school.
<br />

<br />
Crafting is better than EQ, but it's still not all that fun.  You go to harvesting areas and harvest resources (which are copious).  You then go to the appropriate machine, pull out the appropriate tool and start refining it into some useable ingredient.  After that, you can make spells, weapons, armor, etc.
<br />

<br />
Quests are generally obtained from an NPC from a class you're currently in, and center around &quot;Kill X number of monster Y,&quot; &quot;Gather X type of Y resource,&quot; and &quot;Go here and see random guy Q.&quot;
<br />

<br />
The reason why I'm withholding judgement now is that a main part of the game (and one of the coolest aspects, IMO) is the storyline which requires fighters and crafters to band together to repair destroyed cities and other objects (it's a post-apoctalyptic world).  For instance, at the beginning of the game, servers had to work to build bridges and tunnels from the starter cities to the mainland.  The server I was on currently had a serverwide chat channel devoted to &quot;freeing&quot; the tainted elven homeland by running resources to certain parts of the city and then defending against attacks that are triggered by completed repairs.  At a certain stage, all humanoid races became diseased, leaving the dragons to heal them from a plague.
<br />

<br />
However, during the trial period I wasn't strong enough to partake in these adventures, and didn't feel like they were a strong enough draw for me to counteract the boringness of the battle system and quests.  Additionally, it requires the continued interaction of the devs and GMs, which I'm always skeptical of.  It's worth downloading the trial and giving it a shot, though.</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
