			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Horizons.......curious about<a name="27825"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Mar 15 04 1:46 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>Heh... didn't expect to seee this thread here...    
<br />

<br />
For what it's worth, I played Hz a LOT.  In fact, a large chunk of our guild went over there (10 people in total).  So... here's a brief bit about the game that may help those that are still considering it. 
<br />

<br />
- The game had a terrible launch.  It was released in pre-beta state (due to imminent release of other MMO's).  VERY buggy, to the point of unplayability for a good month.  After that, it got better, but was still very buggy. 
<br />
- There are a lot of pluses to the game.  The crafting system is very enjoyable and it's like solo'ing on EQ.  It's the only way to effectively make money in the game, so, you'll end up doing it.  But, you'll actually enjoy it, so don't worry.  Everyone that tried it, liked it.
<br />
- The combat system was kinda neat at first.  Simple, but fun and lots of action.  However, it lacks sophistication.  Ever been on one of those hunts with friends where you go, 'wow, we rock'?  Well, you won't get that feeling in Hz....  ever. But, it is simple and fun to fight.
<br />
- LAG!  OMG, the LAG!!!  Getting more than 10 people together is a sure way to invoke lag-death.  It's really really horrible. Sometimes, even 2 people would suffer the lag.  They may have improved this some.  God, I hope so.
<br />
- The multi-classing system was very neat.  There's very little reason to have alts as you can dauble all over the place.  Little bit of this and that.  And, it seemed to work out fairly well.  And it was fun trying to maximize which classes worked best with what.
<br />
- The game lacks depth.  I know, it's a new game, but it REALLY lacks depth.  There are NO dungeons.  None.  Every place you go is an outdoor area where you can easily skirt every monster in the area and walk right through. Or, you can single pull to your hearts content.  Every item looks the same.  Spells are called, Healing I, Healing II, Fire Bolt III, etc... and are upgraded exactly every 20 levels.  They didn't even attempt to make it interesting.
<br />
- Their implementation of a 'zoneless' world was terrible. Mobs would 'mass-spawn' right in front of you as if to say, 'oops, we weren't ready for you... give us a minute and we'll spread out.. thanks'...
<br />
- You can craft all your equipment. All gear is player made.  That's kinda neat.  Our guild outfitted everyone.  And, you can customize stats for each piece, which has more meaning as you get higher in levels.
<br />
- There is no variety.  Although there are plenty of classes to pick, they are all exactly the same.  Stats mean practically nothing and all classes/spells/weapons seem to be built following rigid mathematical formula that makes every level seem exactly the same.  
<br />

<br />
Anyway, there's some good and bad in the above.  Though, ti's skewed toward the bad because well the game IS bad.  Unfortunately, it's doomed to fail.  There's no way it will survive this year, and will be crushed once the real batch of MMO's come out (WoW, EQ2, Lineage 2). It had too many bugs, not enough content, and there's no incentive to play (for instance, you can build buildings, but, they don't work...  So... why do it?)
<br />

<br />
Oh, one more thing.  Of the 10 peole that left to play, NONE are still playing.  All have quit.  Not all came back to EQ, but, they all quit Horizons.
<br />

<br />
Wyndaria,
<br />
Maestro, Nameless
<br />
</span></td>
